<div class="indented"><a id="comment-10032"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/battlestar/battlestars-daybreak-worst-ending-history-screen-science-fiction#comment-10032" class="active">God in the story</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Tue, 2009-07-14 16:37.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>God as an active, intervening character (which is different from the simple presence of God, or the supernatural in a story) is fundamentally flawed, or perhaps it is less critical to say that it changes greatly the nature of the story.</p>

<p>When a god is pulling the strings, when events are foreordained by this god and the god is intervening to make them happen, the the story becomes god&#8217;s story, and not the characters&#8217; story.   Could Starbuck have been anywhere but at the controls of Galactica when the battle ended?  Or waiting for Leoben out in space to start the alliance?  Or in the maelstrom, being told by an angel to accept death?  Or in the rebuilt viper at the battle of the Ionian nebula?  Starbuck had to be all those places, and do the things she did there.  Same for many other characters (though her life, and Baltar&#8217;s, are the most directly controlled.)</p>

<p>A tiny difference there, veering left instead of right, and Starbuck isn&#8217;t where she is meant to be.</p>

<p>God as a present but distant force is fine.  Characters who believe in God and do things because of their faith &#8212; fine.  Characters that do things because God comes into their head and manipulates them &#8212; no longer characters, just instruments.</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; </div>
  </div>
